  "texts": [
    "Later a more general theory of metric currents, encompassing also currents not of finite mass, was developed by Lang [30] and an analogous question was asked about this type of metric currents.",
    "Our main result is that the conjecture due to Lang for k-currents in R d fails if d ≥ 2 and k ∈ {1,..., d} (see Theorem 1.7).",
    "The original conjecture due to Ambrosio and Kirchheim remains, in general, open.",
    "We discuss the special cases that have been resolved [20,41] in the subsections below.Remarkably, our method relies on connecting the conjecture to the (non-)regularity of a certain partial differential equation (PDE), which is usually called the prescribed Jacobian equation:det Dπ = ρ on Q = [0, 1] d. (1.1)If π is a Lipschitz vector field on Q, then by Rademacher's differentiation theorem, the function det Dπ is defined a.e.",
    "and lies in L ∞ (Q)."
  ],
